body:
Fixes #442 

### Main changes


* Allows a Rib script that can consist of worker invocation function to form the response

```rust

let status = 200;

let start_time = request.path.time;
let end_time = request.path.end_time;
let result = timeline:driver/api/run(start_time, end_time);

{ body: result, status: status }


```

* Make `EvaluationContext` independent of API Gateway use case. This implies, by the time this PR is ready, at least we can say, Rib is fully independent of Golem OSS API Gateway.

Now evaluation-context is

```scala
use golem_wasm_ast::analysis::AnalysedFunction;

#[derive(Clone)]
pub struct EvaluationContext {
    pub variables: Option<TypeAnnotatedValue>,
    pub analysed_functions: Vec<AnalysedFunction>,
}

```

* Make evaluator be able to run the invocation expressions in the Rib Expression Tree
  Functions can exist anywhere in the Rib expression tree, and evaluator will execute it. This is based on an idea I got from John that I went ahead with this. Whether to disallow more than 1 function or not, I am leaving with the team.

* Use double-quotes instead of single quotes (this is a decent change from tokeniser itself) to align with wasm-wave syntax. This will make sure we support all of wasm wave syntax

* Allow users to form variants/enums etc which are simple identifiers until evaluation. Depending on the info in evaluation context, they can be resolved to Enum, Variant, or even function-call. It's even better to feed as much as information about types available (like a symbol table) into the execution context in future. With this PR, the door is opened for it.


@jdegoes  I thought I will have at least this decent shape before we start pairing up. It's even easier to reason about what's in there, and I will be more comfortable to pair up on this branch to bring in type information and fix things.

### Features and fixes

* Support for pattern matching on variants

```scala
// given worker.response TypeAnnotatedValue::Variant { Foo ..}

match worker.response {
   Foo(value) => value.id
   Bar(value) => value.id
}

```

* Fixed nested pattern matching - recursively identify the patterns
```scala
// given worker.response TypeAnnotatedValue::Variant { Foo ..{ Option { Result }

match worker.response {
   Foo(some(ok(value)) => value.id
   Bar(none) => value.id
}
```

* Support on wild card

```scala
match worker.response {
   some(_) => worker.response.id
   none => 'not found'
}
```

* Support on alias

```scala
match worker.response { 
  a @ ok(b @ _) => b 
  c @ err(d @ ok(e)) => {p : c, q: d, r: e.id} 
}

```
* Introduction of TypeMismatch

```scala
// given worker.response is TypeAnnotatedValue::U64(1)

// Following will result in type-mismatch error for the first arm itself - where we tried to match 1 with `ok`
match worker.response {
   ok(_) => "success"
   err(_) => "failure"
}
```

* Stricter pattern matching. Previously any value from worker.response could be considered as `Option::Some`. Now that we moved to `TypeAnnotatedValue` which clearly has `Some` and `None` types for optional values. So we can pattern match strictly, otherwise we get a `TypeMismatch` error.

* Disallowed random constructions. Removed `Expr::Constructor0` to being explicit. That while we can pattern match on any variant, users cannot construct random constructors. 


```scala
// Disallowed
match worker.response {
   some(_) => Foo(1)
   none => 'not found'
}
```

`Expr` cannot evaluate `Foo(1)` because it simply doesn't know what `Foo` is.

* Expr::Result and Expr::Option (and removed Expr::Constructor0)

* Tests in `text` module (for read and write) and `evaluator` module. The ones PR reviewers might be interested in is evaluator, to see the outcome of this PR


* Cleanups that are as follows:
   * Removed higher order functions to evaluate if-else expressions
   * Separate module for if-else, to be consistent with other patterns
   * Removed the complex structure InternalExprResult (which was holding a function insider, on what to do in the next loop). Works well only in Scala!
   * Renaming. A pattern match should consist of `match_expression` and a collection of `arms` and LHS of `arm` is `arm_pattern` and rhs of arm is `arm_body`, following consistent naming around pattern matching expressions in the wild.
   
   
   
There can be many things where we could optimize, I do have an eye on these things, but I think time to take a step back and progress with what we have now, and optimize it with specific tickets in place.
